Neil Chatterjee of Kentucky has been appointed as the Chair of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. Before his confirmation, Chatterjee served as an energy policy advisor to U.S. Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell and played a key role in the passage of major energy, highway, and farm policies. He has also worked for the National Rural Electric Cooperative Association and as an aide to House Republican Conference Chairwoman Deborah Pryce. Chatterjee began his career in Washington with the House Committee on Ways and Means. He is a native of Lexington, Kentucky and holds degrees from St. Lawrence University and the University of Cincinnati College of Law.